<!--
  EtherCAT I/O hardware tree for the Shark project (see Sync/IoManifestParser.cs).
  Originally transcribed from images/devices.jpg (Solution Explorer capture of
  the live PLC_NFL_SHARK project's I/O tree) — but that screenshot's visual
  nesting (Box(CU2508) -> Box(EK1100) -> Terminals) does NOT match how the
  real Shark.tsproj actually stores the tree, confirmed by reading the real
  file's raw XML nesting depth directly (2026-07-14):

  BH1: "Box 1 (CU2508)" and "EK1100_1.1" are SIBLINGS (both direct children of
  BH1) — EK1100_1.1 is the one that actually carries the 8 terminal children.
  BH2: "Box 44 (CU2508)" and "EK1100_2.1" are ALSO siblings of each other, and
  EK1100_2.1 itself has NO children at all — every one of BH2's 19 remaining
  terminals is nested under the FIRST terminal, "EL3174_2.1", not under
  EK1100_2.1 (apparently TwinCAT's own on-disk chain/bus-order representation
  for this coupler, not a real ownership relationship).

  This matters because Sync/IoSyncEngine.cs's DeleteOrphans prunes any real
  direct child not declared here. The previous (wrong) nesting caused
  EK1100_1.1/EK1100_2.1/EL3174_2.1 to look like undeclared orphans and
  triggered DeleteChild on them — which would have deleted almost all of
  BH1/BH2's real hardware (an in-flight COM RPC failure happened to prevent
  the delete from completing; see tasks/todo.md). Keep this manifest's
  nesting in exact sync with the real project's structure, not the
  screenshot's visual grouping — verify against the real .tsproj's raw XML
  indentation before changing this file again.

  Scope: BH1 and BH2 only. BH3/BH4/BH5 (in the same screenshot) are deliberately
  omitted for now:
    - BH3's "Term 33 (EK1100)" coupler's own terminals aren't expanded in the
      screenshot, so its contents are unknown.
    - BH4's boxes (EX260-SEC1, "Mass Flow / Pressure Controller - RJ45" x3) and
      BH5's box (MARPOSS P3XF STANDARD) aren't standard Beckhoff EL/EK catalog
      codes — the exact Product string CreateChild needs to instantiate them
      correctly isn't derivable from the display name alone.
  Add these once confirmed; guessing here risks creating the wrong hardware in
  the live project.

  All devices are Disabled="true" for now: an enabled EtherCAT master with no
  variable linked to a task blocks the build with a modal "needs sync master"
  dialog (see IoManifestParser's doc comment), and no <Links> section exists
  yet for these devices.
-->
